</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>SCR128:v96#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="SCR128"/><meta name="dc:title" content="SCR &#xA;              128-&#xA;                CHAPTERED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div width="100%" style="text-align:center;"><div id="bill_num_title_chap"><span style="text-align:center;font-weight:bold;font-size:1.1em;font-family:'Times New Roman'; "><b>
                Senate Concurrent Resolution
              
                        No. 128</b></span></div><div style="text-align:center;padding-top: 1.0em;padding-bottom: 1.2em;" id="chap_num_title_chap"><span style="font-size:1.4em;font-family:'Times New Roman';font-weight:normal;">
                      CHAPTER 70</span></div></div><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;">Relative to High School Voter Education Weeks.</span></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center">
                  
                  [<span style="  font-size: 1.3em">
                Filed with
              </span><span style="  font-size: 1.3em">
                Secretary of State
              </span> <span style="font-size: 13pt">May 21, 2026.
                      </span>]
                </div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">SCR 128, Pérez.
                          High School Voter Education Weeks.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This measure would declare Monday, April 13, 2026, to Friday, April 24, 2026, inclusive, as High School Voter Education Weeks and would encourage local educational agencies to dedicate at least one of those 2 weeks to educating pupils in grades 9 to 12, inclusive, on the electoral process, as provided. The measure would encourage local educational agencies to provide digital and physical resources necessary to provide this information and would encourage the governing boards or bodies of local educational agencies to contract with third-party nonprofit organizations, as provided, to accomplish this endeavor.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><span class="Resolution" title="source: /caml:MeasureDoc/caml:Resolution&#xA;    "><span class="Whereas" id="id_A90240AC-8821-45C9-B2EF-4C1D73055A00"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Pursuant to Section 49040 of the Education Code, the last two full weeks in April are known as “high school voter education weeks,” during which time persons authorized by the county elections official are allowed to register pupils and school personnel on any high school campus; and </div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_5108FED3-91B9-4412-9653-56462DDFA2F7"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, California is committed to fostering civic engagement and increasing voter participation among youth; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_F5A77C04-2149-4541-99A5-D040B8559D62"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Young people, who represent the next generation of voters and leaders, remain a largely underrepresented group by exhibiting the lowest rates of voter turnout among age groups, and, more broadly, low levels of general civic engagement; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_903EA548-C939-4C52-A3D4-1F0F02E49C01"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, The COVID-19 pandemic, occurring for today’s young people in the midst of essential stages of adolescent development, has created an ethos of disconnection and societal apathy which voids the singular mechanism on which civic engagement and participation in democracy hinge; and</div></span><span class="Whereas" id="id_5D4BF18F-270E-483A-A058-55A2B1C03BA2"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">WHEREAS, Young people should be met in their educational environments, and be provided, with the history, knowledge, and resources to engage in the democratic process, for the purposes of revitalizing community ethos and promoting the importance of civic engagement; now, therefore, be it</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_FE08C560-8997-48DC-8FB5-F4E09EA9793B"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved by the Senate of the State of California, the Assembly thereof concurring, That the Legislature declares Monday, April 13, 2026, to Friday, April 24, 2026, inclusive, as High School Voter Education Weeks; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_967363A1-3288-4B46-8998-AFDEBEFD506D"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That local educational agencies are encouraged to dedicate at least one of the two High School Voter Education Weeks to educating pupils in grades 9 to 12, inclusive, on the electoral process, including, but not limited to, information on the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(1) The importance of youth voting in the election cycle.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(2) Civil discourse.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(3) Election inclusivity and access in a safe manner.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(4) Voter apathy.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(5) The ballot measure process.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(6) Research and information literacy skills.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(7) Methods to improve voter turnout.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(8) Election issues in relation to current societal issues.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(9) History of voter suppression.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(10) Voter registration.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(11) Ballot structure.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(12) Comprehending the electoral college.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(13) Understanding political parties.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(14) Campaigns.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(15) Campaign finance.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(16) Voter identification laws.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(17) Early voting.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(18) Absentee voting.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(19) Using voter education resources.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(20) Understanding technology used in voting systems.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(21) Voting by mail.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(22) Public policy awareness.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(23) Impact of elections on communities.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(24) Civic engagement.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(25) Civic duty.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(26) Political literacy.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(27) Informed
		  voting.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(28) Media literacy in politics.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(29) Intersectionality in politics.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(30) Political empowerment.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(31) Historical disparities in voting rates among socioeconomic, racial, and other identity groups in order to develop pupil understanding of the importance of voting; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_7360E828-1B82-4786-9D50-DC9F3C6120E7"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That local educational agencies are encouraged to provide digital and physical resources necessary to provide this information; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_55CCDF34-68EF-472E-BCB1-8017FA76F489"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That the governing boards or bodies of local educational agencies are encouraged to contract on a volunteer basis with third-party nonprofit organizations that have demonstrated experience in nonpartisan youth civic engagement to accomplish this endeavor; and be it further</div></span><span class="Resolved" id="id_538EB898-81EE-4BF2-AECE-AE7F2149DE43"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Resolved, That the Secretary of the Senate transmit copies of this resolution to the State Department of Education and to the author for appropriate distribution.</div></span></span></div></body></html>
